# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyrillic-digraphs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is used in the Chuvash and in both Eastern Khanty and Northern Khanty alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It appears in some Nenets dictionaries as well.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In certain orthographical varieties of Bulgarian, such as in the Primer with Various Instructions, this letter was used for the sound /ɤ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In modern Bulgarian, this sound is represented by the letter Ъ.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] In Chuvash, ⟨ӑ⟩ represents the mid central vowel [ə], as ⟨a⟩ in word "er**a**".
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is always reduced and can occur stressed only in the first syllable of a polysyllabic word.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] The sound varies in its phonetic realization from a reduced /i/ or [ə] (like the pronunciation of ⟨a⟩ in English "sof**a**") to a labialized version of the ⟨a⟩ in English "**a**ll" (with rounded lips).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-breve-cyrillic] It is sometimes so reduced as to sound coalesced with the following consonant as in сӑтел *table*, /stel/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Nineteenth century polymath Mykhailo Maksymovych used an orthography for the Ukrainian language based on etymological principles of spelling, which included the letter А̂ .
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] This letter is also used in some dialects of South Slavic languages such as Bulgarian and Serbian (e.g. гла̂ва or кра̂к).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-circumflex-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̂ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̂ (U+0302).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It is used in the Khanty, Kildin Sami, Ter Sami, and Hill Mari languages.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Also, this letter was once used in the Gagauz language (which was substituted with ⟨аь⟩).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It was used in the Bashkir language at the end of the 19th century.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] It corresponds to the Cyrillic letter schwa ⟨ә⟩ in modern Bashkir.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] This letter also appears in Bulgarian and Serbian in some of its dialects.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Hill Mari and Gagauz this letter represents the near-open front unrounded vowel, /æ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Kildin Sami and Ter Sami this letter represents the open back unrounded vowel /a/ following a palatalized (sometimes also called "half-palatalized") velar nasal /nʲ/ or one of the alveolar stops /tʲ/ or /dʲ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] In Khanty this letter represents the near-open central vowel /ɐ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] Some languages represent as /ja/, like in letter "Я".
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-diaeresis-cyrillic] A with diaeresis is used in some South Slavic languages, mainly in the Bulgarian and Serbian language to be used for easily shifting the accents in the above languages not only in declensions but elsewhere: брӓт or млāдä.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the Aleut (Bering dialect), Evenki, Ingush, Mansi, Nanai, Orok, Ulch, Kildin Sami, Selkup, and Chechen languages.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron also appears in the Bulgarian and Serbian languages in some dialects.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-macron-cyrillic] A with macron is used in the South Slavic languages mostly in Bulgarian usually used before or after another stressed vowel: **глāвà**, **крāкà**, **овчāрè**, **ковāчè**, **юнāцѝ**, and **граждāнè**.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-macron-cyrillic] Being a relatively recent letter, not present in any legacy 8-bit Cyrillic encoding, the letter А̄ is not represented directly by a precomposed character in Unicode either; it has to be composed as А+◌̄ (U+0304).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Хрэстоматия вейска чили збюр выписов з рожных польских ауторов".
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Грамматыка е̨зыка польскего. На кляссэ̨ I". Въ друкарни р̌а̨довэй пр̌и коммиссыи р̌а̨довэй осьвецэня публичнэго.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-ogonek-cyrillic] *"Lithuania - Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth, Third Partition, Russian Revolution, League of Nations, Klaipėda | Britannica".
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/a-with-ring-above-cyrillic] A with ring above is used only in the alphabet of the Selkup language, where it represents the open-mid back rounded vowel /ɔ/ or the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] The Cyrillic script family contains many specially treated two-letter combinations, or digraphs, but few of these are used in Slavic languages.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] In a few alphabets, trigraphs and even the occasional tetragraph or pentagraph are used.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] In early Cyrillic, the digraphs ⟨оу⟩ and ⟨оѵ⟩ were used for /u/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] As with the equivalent digraph in Greek, they were reduced to a typographic ligature, ⟨ꙋ⟩, and are now written ⟨у⟩.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] The modern letters ⟨ы⟩ and ⟨ю⟩ started out as digraphs, ⟨ъі⟩ and ⟨іо⟩.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] In Church Slavonic printing practice, both historical and modern, ⟨оу⟩ (which is considered as a letter from the alphabet's point of view) is mostly treated as two individual characters, but ⟨ы⟩ is a single letter.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] For example, letter-spacing affects ⟨оу⟩ as if they were two individual letters, and never affects components of ⟨ы⟩.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] In a context of Old Slavonic language, ⟨шт⟩ is a digraph that can replace a letter ⟨щ⟩ and vice versa.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Modern Slavic languages written in the Cyrillic alphabet make little or no use of digraphs.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] There are only two true digraphs: ⟨дж⟩ for /d͡ʒ/ and ⟨дз⟩ for /d͡z/ (Belarusian, Bulgarian, Ukrainian).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Sometimes these digraphs are even considered as special letters of their respective alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] In standard Russian, however, the letters in ⟨дж⟩ and ⟨дз⟩ are always pronounced separately.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Digraph-like letter pairs include combinations of consonants with the soft sign ⟨ь⟩ (Serbian/Macedonian letters ⟨љ⟩ and ⟨њ⟩ are derived from ⟨ль⟩ and ⟨нь⟩), and ⟨жж⟩ or ⟨зж⟩ for the uncommon and optional Russian phoneme /ʑː/.and also ⟨вв⟩ for /v/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Native descriptions of Cyrillic writing system often use the term "digraph" to combinations ⟨ьо⟩ and ⟨йо⟩ (Bulgarian, Ukrainian) as they both correspond to a single letter ⟨ё⟩ of Russian and Belarusian alphabets (⟨ьо⟩ is used for /ʲo/, and ⟨йо⟩ for /jo/).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Cyrillic uses large numbers of digraphs only when used to write non-Slavic languages; in some languages such as Avar, these are completely regular in formation.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Many Caucasian languages use ⟨ә⟩ (Abkhaz), ⟨у⟩ (Kabardian & Adyghe), or ⟨в⟩ (Avar) for labialization, just as many of them, like Russian, use ⟨ь⟩ for palatalization.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Since such sequences are decomposable, regular forms will not be listed below.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Avar uses ⟨в⟩ for labialization, as in хьв /xʷ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] The ь digraphs are spelled this way even before vowels, as in гьабуна /habuna/ "made", not *гябуна.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Note that three of these are tetragraphs.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] However, gemination for the 'strong' consonants in Avar orthography is sporadic, and the simple letters or digraphs are frequently used in their place.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] The vowel digraphs are used for front vowels for other Dagestanian languages and also the local Turkic languages Kumyk and Nogay. ⟨Ӏ⟩ digraphs for ejectives is common across the North Caucasus, as is гӏ for /ɣ~ʁ~ʕ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Kabardian and Adyghe both use ⟨у⟩ for labialization, as in ӏу /ʔʷ/. гу is /ɡʷ/, though г is /ɣ/); ку is /kʷ/, despite the fact that к is not used outside loan words.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Labialized, the trigraph becomes the unusual tetragraph кхъу /qʷ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Tabasaran uses gemination for its 'strong' consonants, but this has a different value with г.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] It uses ⟨в⟩ for labialization of its postalveolar consonants: шв /ʃʷ/, жв /ʒʷ/, чв /tʃʰʷ/, джь /dʒʷ/, ь /tʃʼʷ/, ччь /tʃʷʰː/).
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Tatar has a number of vowels which are written with ambiguous letters that are normally resolved by context, but which are resolved by discontinuous digraphs when context is not sufficient.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] These ambiguous vowel letters are е, front /je/ or back /jɤ/, ю, front /jy/ or back /ju/; and я, front /jæ/ or back /ja/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] They interact with the ambiguous consonant letters к, velar /k/ or uvular /q/, and г, velar /ɡ/ or uvular /ʁ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] In general, velar consonants occur before front vowels and uvular consonants before back vowels, so it is frequently not necessary to specify these values in the orthography.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] A uvular followed by a front vowel, as in /qærdæʃ/ "kinsman", for example, is written with the corresponding back vowel to specify the uvular value: кардәш.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] The front value of а is required by vowel harmony with the following front vowel ә, so this spelling is unambiguous.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] If, however, the proper value of the vowel is not recoverable through vowel harmony, then the letter ь /ʔ/ is added at the end of the syllable, as in шагыйрь /ʃaʁir/ "poet".
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] That is, /i/ is written with a ы rather than a и to show that the г is pronounced /ʁ/ rather than /ɡ/, then the ь is added to show that the ы is pronounced as if it were a и, so the discontinuous digraph ы...ь is used here to write the vowel /i/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] This strategy is also followed with the ambiguous letters е, ю, and я in final syllables, for instance in юнь /jyn/ *cheap*.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] That is, the discontinuous digraphs е...ь, ю...ь, я...ь are used for /j/ plus the front vowels /e, y, æ/.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] Exceptional final-syllable velars and uvulars, however, are written with simple digraphs, with ь for velars and ъ for uvulars: пакь /pak/ *pure*, вәгъдә /wæʁdæ/ *promise*.
[src:cyrillic-digraphs/cyrillic-digraphs] In the Cyrillization of Mandarin, there are digraphs цз and чж, which correspond to Pinyin *z/j* and *zh.* Final *n* is нь, while н stands for final *ng.* юй is *yu,* but ю *you*, ю- *yu-*, -уй *-ui*.
